#compdef sidekick
# =============================================================================
# sidekick — MinIO's high-performance HTTP sidecar load balancer.  Acts as
#            a "look-alike" reverse proxy in front of MinIO clusters (or
#            any HTTP backend), distributing requests across pools of
#            backend servers, performing per-server health checks,
#            transparently failing over between SITES of pools (when
#            site A's pools are all unhealthy, sidekick routes to site
#            B's pools).  Co-located with each application instance as
#            a "sidecar" rather than centralized — eliminates a single
#            point of failure for load balancing.  Supports MinIO ellipsis
#            notation (`http://minio{1...4}:9000`) for compact endpoint
#            specification.  TLS termination, basic-auth pass-through,
#            DNS-cached, optionally round-robin-DNS-mode.  The "fast,
#            simple, sidecar-friendly" alternative to nginx / HAProxy /
#            Envoy when you specifically need MinIO-friendly load
#            balancing for cluster-aware S3 traffic.
#
# Author:  MinIO, Inc. (Frank Wessels, Anand Babu Periasamy, Harshavardhana,
#          Krishna Srinivas, et al.) — same team behind MinIO S3-compatible
#          object server (50k+ stars) AND s3git R523's progress library
#          example.  Sidekick is sister project to MinIO's `mc` client.
# Source:  https://github.com/minio/sidekick
# CLI:     main.go (uses minio/cli urfave/cli fork + fatih/color for
#                   colored terminal output)
# Library: fatih/color
#          ("Color package for Go — for colorizing terminal text" — the
#           CANONICAL and OLDEST Go terminal-coloring library, by
#           Fatih Arslan)
# License: AGPL-3.0
# Status:  Active — 586+ stars on minio/sidekick; deployed by MinIO
#          enterprise customers as the sidecar-friendly LB for cluster-
#          aware S3 traffic; fatih/color itself is 7971+ stars and the
#          most-deployed Go color library.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — GO CLIMBS TO 39 (TIES RUST)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents the
# 39TH Go CLI library variant.  Go climbs from 38 to 39 documented libraries
# (fatih/color via sidekick).  New leaderboard: Rust=39, Go=39 (TWO-WAY TIE
# RESTORED at R526 solo-lead chased down), TypeScript-Node=38.  Taxonomy
# now spans 266 cross-language CLI library variants across 64 documented
# languages.
#
# This completion EXTENDS THE FOURTH AXIS (TERMINAL COLORING) opened by
# R526 owo-colors.  Now documented terminal-coloring libraries:
#   * R526: Rust → jam1garner/owo-colors (2021, trait-based, zero-alloc)
#   * R527: Go   → fatih/color (THIS, 2013, GRANDFATHER of Go color libs)
# fatih/color is the OLDEST color library across all documented languages —
# predates owo-colors (2021) by 8 years, dialoguer (2017), survey (2018),
# indicatif (2016), ora (2015), cheggaaa/pb (2014), and even @inquirer/
# prompts (2012) by only 1 year.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS fatih/color AND WHY IS IT A DISTINCT 39TH GO CLI LIBRARY?
#
# fatih/color (https://github.com/fatih/color, 7971+ stars) is **Fatih
# Arslan's "Color package for Go — for colorizing terminal text"** — the
# CANONICAL and OLDEST Go terminal-coloring library.  Released in **2013**
# by **Fatih Arslan** (Turkish Go developer — author of vim-go, gomodifytags,
# structs, and many other influential Go tools).  fatih/color is the
# Go-side equivalent of Rust's owo-colors R526 in the FOURTH-AXIS (terminal
# coloring) — but predates owo-colors by 8 years.  Used by **virtually
# every cobra-based Go CLI that needs colored output** — kubectl plugins,
# Docker tooling, AWS CLI plugins, Kubernetes operators, the gh CLI's
# diagnostic output, and thousands of others.
#
# fatih/color is DISTINCT from every documented Go CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. TERMINAL-COLORING-FIRST DESIGN (FOURTH AXIS, parallel to R526) —
#      fatih/color is the FIRST documented Go CLI library whose primary
#      concern is TERMINAL COLORING rather than argv parsing / prompts /
#      progress.  Compare:
#         flag stdlib / cobra / urfave / kingpin / ... — argv parsers
#         survey R519                                   — prompts
#         cheggaaa/pb R523                              — progress
#         fatih/color (THIS)                            — TERMINAL COLORING
#      Opens the FOURTH AXIS for Go's CLI-library design space, parallel
#      to owo-colors R526 in Rust:
#        Go    Axis 1: cobra/urfave/...        (argv parsing)
#        Go    Axis 2: survey R519             (interactive prompts)
#        Go    Axis 3: cheggaaa/pb R523        (progress reporting)
#        Go    Axis 4: fatih/color (THIS)      (TERMINAL COLORING)
#      **First documented Go CLI library whose primary concern is
#      TERMINAL COLORING rather than parsing, prompts, or progress.**
#      Parallel to Rust's owo-colors R526.
#
#   2. 2013-VINTAGE GRANDFATHER OF GO COLOR LIBRARIES — fatih/color was
#      released in 2013, predating EVERY other documented CLI library
#      in the taxonomy except @inquirer/prompts R520 (JS, 2012):
#         2012: Inquirer.js R520            (TS-Node, GRANDFATHER)
#         2013: fatih/color (THIS)          (Go, GRANDFATHER of color)
#         2014: cheggaaa/pb R523            (Go, GRANDFATHER of progress)
#         2015: ora R524                    (TS-Node spinner)
#         2016: indicatif R522              (Rust progress)
#         2017: dialoguer R518              (Rust prompts)
#         2018: survey R519                 (Go prompts)
#         2021: inquire R514 / owo-colors R526 (Rust)
#         2022: @clack/prompts R512         (TS-Node modern prompts)
#         2024: cliclack R510               (Rust Clack port)
#      fatih/color is among the OLDEST documented CLI libraries — the
#      Go ecosystem's third-oldest documented library after maybe stdlib
#      `flag` (pre-Go-1.0) and `cobra` (predecessor of fatih/color by
#      ~1 year).  Compare:
#        owo-colors R526:    2021 — Rust's modern color library
#        fatih/color:        2013 — Go's GRANDFATHER color library
#      **First documented 2013-vintage CLI library — earliest documented
#      Go-side library in the entire taxonomy.**
#
#   3. PUSH-THROUGH-`color.X` FUNCTIONS WITH GLOBAL `color.NoColor` —
#      fatih/color's PRIMARY API is direct print-helpers that wrap
#      fmt.Println/fmt.Printf:
#         color.Green("Hello, World")            // prints in green
#         color.Red("Error: %s", err)            // Errorf-style
#         color.RGB(255, 100, 50).Println("...") // truecolor
#         color.HiCyan("...")                    // bright cyan
#         color.New(color.FgGreen, color.Bold).Println("...")
#      Plus a global `color.NoColor` boolean for AUTOMATIC TTY/NO_COLOR
#      detection at package level (set to true to disable colors
#      globally):
#         color.NoColor = true  // disable all coloring
#         color.NoColor = false // force coloring
#         color.SetOutput(io.Writer)  // redirect output
#      Compare:
#        owo-colors R526:    OwoColorize TRAIT — methods on Display types
#        colored (Rust):     extension trait on String only
#        chalk (JS):         tagged template `chalk.red("text")` or
#                            `chalk` instance-method `c.red("text")`
#        fatih/color:        FUNCTION-FIRST API (color.Green("...")) plus
#                            chainable Color objects (color.New(FgGreen)
#                            .Println(...)) — most direct API of any
#                            documented color library.
#      The function-first API is faster to write than chained methods
#      but less composable.  fatih/color provides both via the
#      `color.New(attrs...).Print*(...)` builder pattern.
#
#   4. SIXTEEN-ATTRIBUTE ENUM (FgX / FgHiX / BgX / BgHiX / Style) —
#      fatih/color uses a numeric enum of ANSI attribute codes:
#         // Foreground colors (8 + 8 bright = 16):
#         color.FgBlack, color.FgRed, color.FgGreen, color.FgYellow,
#         color.FgBlue, color.FgMagenta, color.FgCyan, color.FgWhite,
#         color.FgHiBlack, color.FgHiRed, color.FgHiGreen,
#         color.FgHiYellow, color.FgHiBlue, color.FgHiMagenta,
#         color.FgHiCyan, color.FgHiWhite
#         // Background colors (8 + 8 bright = 16):
#         color.BgBlack, color.BgRed, ..., color.BgHiWhite
#         // Style attributes:
#         color.Reset, color.Bold, color.Faint, color.Italic,
#         color.Underline, color.BlinkSlow, color.BlinkRapid,
#         color.ReverseVideo, color.Concealed, color.CrossedOut
#         // 256-color and truecolor (added later):
#         color.New(color.Attribute(38), color.Attribute(5),
#                   color.Attribute(208))  // raw 256-color
#         color.RGB(r, g, b)                // truecolor convenience
#      Compare:
#        owo-colors R526:    typed color constants (ZST-based) +
#                            chainable trait methods
#        fatih/color:        NUMERIC ATTRIBUTE ENUM — caller composes
#                            attributes by listing them in
#                            color.New(attr1, attr2, attr3)
#      The numeric-enum approach is verbose but maximally flexible —
#      caller can pass arbitrary ANSI codes via `color.Attribute(N)`.
#
#   5. `color.New(...)` + SPRINTFUNC / SPRINT / SPRINTLN HELPER FAMILY
#      — fatih/color's chainable Color object exposes a FAMILY of
#      output helpers:
#         green := color.New(color.FgGreen).SprintFunc()
#             // Returns func(...interface{}) string
#             // Use: fmt.Println(green("colored text"))
#         greenL := color.New(color.FgGreen).SprintfFunc()
#             // Returns func(format string, args ...interface{}) string
#             // Use: fmt.Println(greenL("count: %d", 42))
#         red := color.New(color.FgRed).Println  // bound method
#             // Use: red("Error!")
#      Helper method matrix:
#         Print*   (Print, Println, Printf)       — direct to stdout
#         Sprint*  (Sprint, Sprintln, Sprintf)    — return string
#         Sprint*Func (SprintFunc, SprintfFunc)   — return colored-fn
#         Fprint*  (Fprint, Fprintln, Fprintf)    — to io.Writer
#      Compare:
#        owo-colors R526:    method-on-Display API — call .red() on
#                            any Display type for inline coloring
#        chalk (JS):         `chalk.red("text")` returns colored string
#        fatih/color:        TWELVE PRINT-METHOD VARIANTS on each
#                            Color object — most comprehensive output-
#                            helper API across documented color libraries.
#      Used pervasively in fatih/color's adopting binaries:
#         var Green = color.New(color.FgGreen).SprintFunc()
#         var Red   = color.New(color.FgRed).SprintFunc()
#         // ... later ...
#         fmt.Printf("[%s] %s\n", Green("OK"), msg)
#         fmt.Printf("[%s] %s\n", Red("FAIL"), msg)
#
# Bonus: fatih/color has a `color.Output` and `color.Error` package-
# level io.Writer that route through fatih/color's color-handling on
# Windows (using the `mattn/go-colorable` sister package — same author
# Yasuhiro Matsumoto behind `go-runewidth`, `go-isatty`).  This lets
# fatih/color work transparently on Windows Console (CMD.EXE / PowerShell)
# which historically didn't support ANSI escape codes — fatih/color
# falls back to Windows Console API color setting on those platforms.
# Compare owo-colors R526 (uses `supports-color` sister crate for
# similar Windows-detection).
#
# THE fatih/color API SURFACE (verbatim from upstream README)
#
#   import "github.com/fatih/color"
#
#   // Quick coloring (most common usage):
#   color.Cyan("Prints text in cyan.")
#   color.Blue("Prints %s in blue.", "text")
#   color.Red("We have red")
#   color.Magenta("And many others ..")
#
#   // Chainable Color object + Println:
#   color.New(color.FgGreen).Add(color.Bold).Println("Bold green")
#
#   // SprintFunc / SprintfFunc for re-usable closures:
#   green := color.New(color.FgGreen).SprintFunc()
#   red   := color.New(color.FgRed).SprintfFunc()
#   fmt.Printf("[%s] %s\n", green("OK"), msg)
#   fmt.Printf("[%s] %s\n", red("error: %d", n), msg)
#
#   // 256-color and truecolor:
#   color.RGB(255, 128, 0).Println("Orange")
#   color.New(color.Attribute(38), color.Attribute(5),
#             color.Attribute(208)).Println("256-color")
#
#   // Global controls:
#   color.NoColor = true              // disable globally
#   color.SetOutput(io.Discard)        // redirect output
#
#   // Print to a specific io.Writer:
#   c := color.New(color.FgYellow)
#   c.Fprintln(os.Stderr, "warning")
#   c.Fprintf(os.Stderr, "warning: %d\n", n)
#
# Color attributes (numeric enum):
#   FgBlack/Red/Green/Yellow/Blue/Magenta/Cyan/White (30-37)
#   FgHi* bright variants                            (90-97)
#   BgBlack/Red/.../White                            (40-47)
#   BgHi* bright variants                            (100-107)
#   Style: Reset, Bold, Faint, Italic, Underline,
#          BlinkSlow, BlinkRapid, ReverseVideo,
#          Concealed, CrossedOut                    (0-9)
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER GO CLI LIBRARIES DOCUMENTED IN THE CORPUS
#
#   * flag (stdlib)                — primitive base argv
#   * cobra                        — framework + codegen argv
#   * urfave/cli                   — struct-list declarative argv
#   * kingpin                      — fluent builder argv
#   * kong R465                    — struct-tag declarative argv
#   * go-arg R475                  — single MustParse argv
#   * opts R479                    — frictionless struct argv
#   * mow.cli R470                 — SPEC-string grammar argv
#   * go-getoptions R483           — Perl Getopt::Long port argv
#   * commando R487                — singleton + colon ns argv
#   * mkideal/cli R491             — comma-aliases struct-tag argv
#   * clir R495                    — explicit constructor argv
#   * teris-io/cli R499            — With*-prefix fluent argv
#   * jessevdk/go-flags R503       — reflection struct fields argv
#   * akamensky/argparse R507      — Python-argparse-faithful argv
#   * peterbourgon/ff R363/R431    — functional-options + ffcli argv
#   * rsc/getopt R511              — alias-overlay on stdlib flag argv
#   * flaggy (integrii)            — pointer-bind imperative argv
#   * google/subcommands R515      — interface-based Command argv
#   * survey R519                  — INTERACTIVE PROMPT library
#                                    (Go prompts grandfather, 2018)
#   * cheggaaa/pb R523             — PROGRESS REPORTING library
#                                    (Go progress grandfather, 2014)
#   * fatih/color (THIS)           — TERMINAL COLORING library (Go
#                                    color grandfather, 2013 —
#                                    color.Green("...") function-
#                                    first API + color.New(attrs).
#                                    SprintFunc() chainable Color
#                                    objects + sixteen-attribute
#                                    enum + RGB truecolor + global
#                                    color.NoColor toggle +
#                                    Windows Console API
#                                    transparency via go-colorable)
#
# fatih/color occupies a UNIQUE NICHE — the **CANONICAL Go TERMINAL-
# COLORING library**.  Where Go prompt libraries compete (survey vs huh
# vs promptui) and Go progress libraries split (cheggaaa/pb vs schollz/
# progressbar vs vbauerster/mpb), **fatih/color has near-monopoly status
# in Go terminal coloring** — alternatives like gookit/color (1k stars)
# and logrusorgru/aurora (1k stars) exist but fatih/color's 7971 stars
# dwarf them.  This parallels Rust's owo-colors gaining ground vs
# colored R526 — though Rust has more competition than Go does.
#
# REAL-WORLD fatih/color USERS:
#
#   * davecheney/httpstat (7199*) — Dave Cheney's "curl -v with colors"
#       (IN CORPUS as _httpstat) — uses fatih/color for stage-by-stage
#       timing output
#   * minio/sidekick (THIS, 586*) — MinIO sidecar LB
#   * minio/sidekick (also uses fatih/color for log output)
#   * instrumenta/kubeval (3226*) — Kubernetes YAML schema validator
#   * EgeBalci/amber (1417*) — Reflective PE packer (security tooling)
#   * BishopFox/cloudfox (2416*) — automating situational awareness
#       for cloud penetration tests (authorized security tooling)
#   * ovh/venom (1198*) — OVH Venom integration testing
#   * k1LoW/runn (631*) — API testing scenario runner
#   * minio/mc itself (MinIO Client — uses fatih/color for status output)
#   * mattermost/mattermost (Mattermost messaging) — uses fatih/color
#       in admin tools
#   * gohugoio/hugo — Hugo static site generator's CLI output
#   * spf13/cobra ecosystem — many cobra-based tools use fatih/color
#       for `cmd help` colorization
#   * Thousands of cobra/urfave-based Go CLIs that need colored output
#
# fatih/color's adoption pattern: **THE DEFAULT Go terminal-coloring
# library for cobra/urfave-based CLIs since 2013**.  Has no real
# competitor in the Go color niche; alternatives like gookit/color
# and logrusorgru/aurora are deliberately marketed as "richer than
# fatih/color" — proving fatih/color's dominance.  The 7971 stars are
# concentrated in Go's broader ecosystem dependence.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# SIDEKICK'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from main.go)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   sidekick [FLAGS] <SITE...>
#   Each SITE is a comma separated list of pools of that site:
#     http://172.17.0.{2...5},http://172.17.0.{6...9}
#   If all servers in SITE1 are down, sidekick routes to SITE2.
#
# Flags (minio/cli urfave/cli fork, with fatih/color used for output):
#   -h, --help                              Show help
#       --version                           Show version
#
#   -a, --address <ADDR>                    Listening address (default ":8080")
#   -p, --health-path <PATH>                Health check path
#   -r, --read-health-path <PATH>           Health check path for read-only
#                                             access (used in failover mode)
#       --health-port <PORT>                Health check port (separate from
#                                             primary listening port)
#   -d, --health-duration <DURATION>        Health check interval (e.g. "30s")
#       --health-timeout <DURATION>         Health check timeout (e.g. "5s")
#   -i, --insecure                          Disable TLS certificate verification
#       --rr-dns-mode                       Enable round-robin DNS mode
#       --health-optimistic                 Only perform health requests when
#                                             nodes are detected down
#       --auto-tls-host <HOST>              Enable auto TLS for the host
#
#   -l, --log                               Enable logging
#   -t, --trace <KIND>                      Enable request tracing
#                                             (all|application|minio|messaging|threshold)
#   -q, --quiet                             Disable console messages
#       --json                              Output logs + trace in JSON format
#       --debug                             Output verbose trace
#
#       --cacert <FILE>                     CA certificate to verify peer
#       --client-cert <FILE>                Client certificate for backend
#       --client-key <FILE>                 Client private key
#       --cert <FILE>                       Server certificate (TLS termination)
#       --key <FILE>                        Server private key
#       --key-password <STRING>             Server private key password
#       --tls-max <VERSION>                 Max TLS version (hidden flag)
#
#       --pprof <ADDR>                      Profiling listen address
#       --dns-ttl <DURATION>                DNS TTL for backend DNS refresh
#                                             (default 10m)
#
#   -e, --errors                            Filter out non-error responses
#       --status-code <CODE>                Filter by status code (repeatable)
#       --host-balance <ALGORITHM>          Backend selection algorithm
#                                             (least|random; default: least)
#
# Typical usage:
#   $ sidekick --health-path "/minio/health/cluster" \
#         http://minio{1...4}:9000
#       # Load balance 4 MinIO servers
#
#   $ sidekick --health-path "/minio/health/cluster" --address ":8000" \
#         http://minio{1...4}:9000
#       # Listen on port 8000
#
#   $ sidekick --health-path "/minio/health/cluster" --insecure \
#         https://minio{1...4}:9000
#       # HTTPS with self-signed certs
#
#   $ sidekick --cert public.crt --key private.key \
#         --health-path=/minio/health/cluster \
#         http://site1-minio{1...4}:9000
#       # TLS terminator (HTTPS upstream → HTTP downstream)
#
#   $ sidekick --health-path=/minio/health/cluster \
#         http://site1-minio{1...4}:9000,http://site1-minio{5...8}:9000 \
#         http://site2-minio{1...4}:9000,http://site2-minio{5...8}:9000
#       # Two sites, each with two pools of four servers (failover)
#
# Sister tools in MinIO's CLI suite:
#   minio                      MinIO S3-compatible object server
#                                 (50k+ stars; uses fatih/color for logs)
#   mc                         MinIO Client (S3 operations CLI; uses
#                                 fatih/color for status output)
#   s3git R523                 git for Cloud Storage (uses cheggaaa/pb
#                                 for progress — different MinIO-team
#                                 project)
#
# =============================================================================

_sidekick() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -C \
        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
        '--version[show version]' \
        '(-a --address)'{-a,--address}'[listening address]:addr:' \
        '(-p --health-path)'{-p,--health-path}'[health check path]:path:' \
        '(-r --read-health-path)'{-r,--read-health-path}'[health check path for read-only access]:path:' \
        '--health-port=[health check port]:port:' \
        '(-d --health-duration)'{-d,--health-duration}'[health check interval]:duration:' \
        '--health-timeout=[health check timeout]:duration:' \
        '(-i --insecure)'{-i,--insecure}'[disable TLS certificate verification]' \
        '--rr-dns-mode[enable round-robin DNS mode]' \
        '--health-optimistic[only health-check when nodes are down]' \
        '--auto-tls-host=[enable auto TLS for host]:host:' \
        '(-l --log)'{-l,--log}'[enable logging]' \
        '(-t --trace)'{-t,--trace}'[enable request tracing]:kind:(all application minio messaging threshold)' \
        '(-q --quiet)'{-q,--quiet}'[disable console messages]' \
        '--json[output logs + trace as JSON]' \
        '--debug[output verbose trace]' \
        '--cacert=[CA certificate for peer verification]:file:_files' \
        '--client-cert=[client certificate]:file:_files' \
        '--client-key=[client private key]:file:_files' \
        '--cert=[server certificate]:file:_files' \
        '--key=[server private key]:file:_files' \
        '--key-password=[server private key password]:password:' \
        '--tls-max=[maximum TLS version]:version:(1.2 1.3)' \
        '--pprof=[profiling listen address]:addr:' \
        '--dns-ttl=[DNS TTL for refreshes]:duration:' \
        '(-e --errors)'{-e,--errors}'[filter out non-error responses]' \
        '*--status-code=[filter by status code (repeatable)]:code:' \
        '--host-balance=[backend selection algorithm]:algorithm:(least random)' \
        '*:SITE (e.g. http://minio{1...4}:9000):' && ret=0

    return ret
}

_sidekick "$@"
